## The Programmer's Nightmare

What happens if the loop condition NEVER becomes false?

```javascript
for (let i = 1; i > 0; i++) {
  console.log("Help I am stuck!");
}
```

Because `i` starts at 1 and keeps going UP, `i > 0` will ALWAYS be true! The loop will run forever, using up all memory, and crashing your browser tab.

**Always make sure your loops have a reachable exit!**
